\begin_layout Subsection
Explanation for curvature-driven interface motion and counter-term effect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Basically the idea behind these counter terms is that we want the interface
 to behave as if it was plane.
 The difference of behavior between planar and curved interfaces can be
 explained by an energy dissipation principle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Allen-Cahn equation used for the phase field in our model is derived
 from an energy functional, where we assume temporal variations negatively
 proportional to the derivative of the functional with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, ie
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\phi}{\partial t}=-m_{\phi}\frac{\delta\Omega}{\delta\phi}
\]

\end_inset

In this energy functional, the interfacial energy is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\boldsymbol{\nabla}\phi\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then if we look at a curved interface, we can see that the interfacial
 energy will be higher on one side of the interface, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:planar_vs_curved"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Then, the evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 through the phase-field equation will be such that this interfacial energy
 becomes homogeneous.
 The interfacial energy from the higher energy zone will then move toward
 the lower energy zone, following the green arrow from the figure.
 Effectively, this is done through the interface's movement toward the curved
 interface's interior, because the interfacial energy is localized inside
 the interface.
\end_layout

