\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Curvature effects at interface arise because a curved interface causes an
 excess of chemical/thermal energy, because of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

increased area of contact
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, at least from the point of view of small length along the interface (that
 is the capillary length).
 Thermodynamic principle thus act to remove this excess energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The structure of the phase field equation is able to implicitly account
 for this excess energy, with a capillary length proportional to interface
 width.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
